><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role><gtr:role><gtr:name>FELLOW</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=ES%2FI004599%2F1"><gtr:id>E713A42A-D711-496E-B55E-8DA9A1B10516</gtr:id><gtr:title>The Consequences of Meta-stereotyping for Members of Disadvantaged Groups</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/I004599/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>Social interaction - especial those involving people of different social groups - is often laden with people's beliefs about the way an outgroup interaction partner may perceive one's own group. These so called 'meta-stereotypes', as previous&lt;br />research has shown, influence the attitudes and behaviour of members of dominant group towards members of a disadvantaged outgroup. In comparison, littie is known about the effect of metastereotyping among members of disadvantaged groups.&lt;/p>

&lt;p>The research conducted during the investigator's PhD tried to address this issue. Specifically that body of work examined the effect of meta-stereotyping on outcomes such as:&lt;/p>

&lt;ul>
 

 &lt;li>orientation towards social protest&lt;/li>

 &lt;li>&amp;nbsp;pro-social behaviour towards a higher status outgroup&lt;/li>

 &lt;li>&amp;nbsp;perceived discrimination, well-being and perceived employability prospects - using a variety of methods (eg, experimental and cross-sectional stijdies).&lt;/li>

&lt;/ul>

&lt;p>The findings revealed that attitudes and behaviour of members of disadvantaged groups towards the dominant outgroup are guided by the need to improve their social identity, and that focusing on (negative) metastereotypes can lower the subjective well-being of group members.&lt;/p>

&lt;p>This fellowship will enable the researcher to:&lt;/p>

&lt;ul>
 

 &lt;li>&amp;nbsp; publish and disseminate ttie findings widely&lt;/li>

 &lt;li>&amp;nbsp; write one research proposal to pursue further research goals&lt;/li>

 &lt;li>&amp;nbsp; update on qualitative research method.&lt;/li>

&lt;/ul>

